<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written submission to House of Commons Health Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from UK Public Health Register (PHE0005)</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Summary</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England and its partners face a challenging agenda in relation to England’s public health policy objectives and the need to develop an effective public health workforce capable of delivering them.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The creation of an effective public health workforce can be achieved through three current and inter-related initiatives: a workforce which trains within the Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework, a Skills Passport which evidences that training and  registration of public health specialists and practitioners</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK Public Health Register which regulates all Public Health Specialists and increasingly the largely unregulated practitioners not regulated by the Medical and Dental Regulators works with Public Health England on these initiatives and on workforce issues more generally</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England and the UK Public Health Register (UKPHR) share an agenda:  delivery of England’s new </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Public Health Workforce Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Central to this are the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (known as the Public Health Skills and Careers Framework until its refresh during 2013), the proposal for a public health workforce </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">skills passport</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the arrangements for regulation of this workforce, including through </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UKPHR registration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR has been a voluntary register for public health specialists in the UK since the opening of Public Health specialist practice to a range of disciplines beyond dentistry and medicine in 2003. Employers have come to value the assurance of professional competence that registration evidences.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> New recruits are now required by employers to be registered with UKPHR (unless already regulated by one of the statutory regulators, the General Medical Council or General Dental Council).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Since 2011, UKPHR has piloted voluntary registration of public health practitioners in England, Wales and Scotland as well.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is intended that registration of practitioners will offer employers the same assurance of professional competence as is currently available for specialists.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The purpose of registration is, first and foremost, to protect the public and promote public confidence in public health practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Clearly for practitioners who engage with individual members of the public through sexual health services, obesity interventions, smoking cessation programmes and similar initiatives such protection is especially important.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR has to date worked with Public Health England in respect of:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Transforming the existing practitioner registration pilot schemes around the UK into a UK-wide scheme, with a target of a 2014 launch;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Investigation of the policy and practice issues which will need to be addressed in order to introduce successfully a Skills Passport for individual members of the public health workforce;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Discussions about implementation of revalidation for public health specialists (not covered by the General Medical Council’s revalidation scheme);</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Participation in the activities of the Public Health Workforce Advisory Group.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These and other key issues for public health in the UK and Public Health England’s contribution to addressing them are discussed in the following paragraphs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As the Public Health Workforce Strategy acknowledges information about the size, make-up and activities of the existing public health workforce is poor. Public Health England therefore faces a huge challenge in delivering the step-change in public health performance that the Government’s Public Health Outcomes Framework signals. Public Health England will struggle to make a real difference in public health effectiveness if it is unable to identify and work with the key elements of the public health workforce.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England is getting to grips with this most challenging public health workforce issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> First, it is addressing the need to assess its own workforce, transferred in from over 100 organisations, and understand its own capabilities and the effective working relationships it already has with its public health partners. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Secondly, Public Health England recognises the powerful tool that the combination of (a) the Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework; (b) the skills passport and (c) UKPHR registration will become for identifying, developing and making effective the public health workforce as a whole.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR’s most direct involvement with Public Health England relates to our current ambitious project for the establishment of a UK-wide voluntary register of public health practitioners. UKPHR’s pilot schemes have resulted in the registration of the first 100 practitioners who have compiled portfolios which have been assessed as evidencing “autonomous public health practice at Level 5 or above in the Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework”. Evaluation reports demonstrate that this process is robust and is valued by registrants and employers alike. UKPHR understands that Public Health England shares its judgement that a UK-wide register is both practicable and valuable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whilst practitioner registration is currently based on voluntary regulation, we are undergoing the process of achieving Accredited Voluntary Register status with the Professional Standards Authority. If at any stage public policy decision-makers were to prefer a statutory model of regulation of this public health workforce, UKPHR </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would willingly offer for this accreditation to be converted into that of a statutory regulator.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England is leading on the proposal to create a Skills Passport for individual members of the public health workforce. UKPHR is a member of Public Health England’s steering group for this project and sees great synergy between registration and the skills passport.  It enables sight and knowledge of the wider public health workforce and delivery of key messages about the skills and knowledge and ethical conduct that individuals need to attain registration later in their careers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR is committed to introducing a requirement for revalidation for registrants who are public health specialists. It is unfortunate that Public Health England is unable to assist with the implementation of this key development at the current time, citing capacity and awaiting the outcome of a Department of Health consultation about statutory regulation of specialists. We remain convinced of its importance if public health specialists however regulated are to have equivalent status in the eyes of their employers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public Health England and UKPHR are active contributors to the Public Health Workforce Advisory Group (PHWAG). This Group has been pleased to assist in the identification of the East Midlands LETB (Local Education &amp; Training Board) as lead LETB for public health careers and the successful transfer of the PHORCaST website</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to East Midlands LETB’s supervision. More widely, this is a crucial time for Health Education England to be engaging with the education and training needs of the public health workforce and PHWAG is helping to play a vital role in engineering this engagement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As stated, UKPHR operates a register for the regulation of public health and specialists for the primary purpose of public protection. UKPHR looks to a productive partnership with Public Health England to secure the public’s safety as well as the public’s improved health and reduced health inequalities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> UKPHR believes that these crucially important objectives will only be met if there is a public health workforce which is coherently organised, has the necessary assured skills and knowledge and whose professional competence is achieved and maintained through high standards of education and training, Continuing Professional Development and regular revalidation. Public Health England has a hugely significant role to play both as an exemplar of good practice in its own operations and as a leader of the public health workforce more widely. We look forward to working with Public Health England to make a success of this role.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UKPHR is willing to provide further comment and evidence in support and is willing to contribute oral evidence to the Committee if requested.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:10pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#004600; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Healthy Lives, Healthy People: A Public Health Workforce Strategy </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/govern%20%20ment/publications/healthy-lives-healthy-people-a-public-workforce-strategy"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/govern  ment/publications/healthy-lives-healthy-people-a-public-workforce-strategy</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> PHORCaST Public Health Online Resource for Careers, Skills and Training </span><a href="http://www.phorcast.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.phorcast.org.uk/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>